properties.name: AuthenticationMode
properties.description: Authentication Mode attribute enables to define the authentication mode used for the user s password check. Authentication modes managed within HOPEX are:- MEGA: the HOPEX authentication service checks that the password entered matches the password stored (hached and encrypted)  in HOPEX repository.- LDAP: passwords are managed and stored in an LDAP directory. The settings of the directory are stored in HOPEX s options.- WINDOWS (deprecated): authentication: passwords are managed and stored in Windows. It also enables the user connected through Windows to be automatically recognized in HOPEX, therefore its password is not prompted.

properties.name: MetaAttributeType
properties.description: This parameter defines the internal type of a MetaAttribute.Possible values: 	String: X. Use it for alphanumeric and numeric values if not used to compute data. Value must belong to [0-1024]  	VarChar: A. ANSI. Use it for large texts like comments 	Datetime: D. Use it for dates 	Boolean: 1. Values are 0 or 1. Not recommended. Use rather String with a tabulated values 	Short: S. Use it for small numbers if you compute data. Value must belong to [0-65535] 	Double: H. Use it for numbers if you compute data. Value must belong to [0-18446744073709551616] 	Long: L. Value must belong to [0-4294967295] 	Float: F. Use it for large numbers if you compute data.  	Binary: Q. Internal. Do not use it 	VarBinary: B. Internal. Do not use itNote: the internal format of date is  YYYY MM DD HH:MM:SS

properties.name: MetaAttributeLength

properties.name: MetaAttributeFormat
properties.description: This parameter defines for a metamodel element (MetaAttribute, TaggedValue) the appropriate control for the MetaAttributePossible values: 	Standard: S (default). Use it for strings. 	Enumeration: F: use it string type with predefined list of values 	Enumeration (Opened): T. Use it for string type with list of values open to user input 	Duration: D. Use it for dates 	Percent: P. Use it to display percentages 	Double: E. Use it to display numbers 	Object: O. Use it to display objects 	Signed Number: Z. Use it to display signed numbers. 	Relative: R. Internal. Do not use it.

enumValues.description: TOGAF Networked Computing/Hardware Diagram - TOGAF Networked Computing/Hardware DiagramStarting with the transformation to client-server systems from mainframes and later with the advent of e-Business and J2EE, large enterprises moved predominantly into a highly network based distributed network computing environment with firewalls and demilitarized zones.Currently, most of the applications have a web front-end and, looking at the deploymentarchitecture of these applications, it is very common to find three distinct layers in the network landscape; namely a web presentation layer, an business logic or application layer, and a backend data store layer. enumValues.name: TOGAFUseCaseDiagram_TUCD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Use Case Diagram - TOGAF Use Case DiagramA Business Use-Case diagram displays the relationships between consumers and providers of business services. Business services are consumed by actors or other business services and the Business Use-Case diagram provides added richness in describing business capability by illustrating how and when that capability is used.The purpose of the Business Use-Case diagram is to help to describe and validate the interaction between actors and their roles to processes and functions. As the architecture progresses, the use-case can evolve from the business level to include data, application, and technology details. Architectural business use-cases can also be re-used in systems design work.

enumValues.name: TOGAFApplicationAndUserLocationDiagram_TAULD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Application and User Location Diagram - TOGAF Application and User Location DiagramThe Application and User Location diagram shows the geographical distribution of applications.It can be used to show where applications are used by the end user; the distribution of where the host application is executed and or delivered in thin client scenarios; the distribution of where applications are developed, tested, and released; etc.Analysis can reveal opportunities for rationalization, as well as duplication and or gaps.The purpose of this diagram is to clearly depict the business locations from which business users typically interact with the applications, but also the hosting location of the application infrastr ucture.The diagram enables:- Identification of the number of package instances needed to sufficiently support the user population that may be spread out geographically- Estimation of the number and the type of user licenses for the package or other software- Estimation of the level of support needed for the users and location of support center- Selection of system management tools, structure, and management system required to support the enterprise users customers partners both locally and remotely- Appropriate planning for the technological components of the business, namely server sizing and network bandwidth, etc.- Performance considerations while implementing application and technology architecture solutionsUsers typically interact with applications in a variety of ways; for example:- To support the operations of the business day-to-day- To participate in the execution of a business process- To access information (look-up, read)- To develop the application- To administer and maintain the application

enumValues.name: Micro_ServiceStructureDiagram_MicroServStructDiag
enumValues.description: Micro-Service Structure Diagram - Micro-Service Structure DiagramA Micro-Service Structure Diagram graphically shows first level components of a micro-service: micro-services, IT services, data stores, the access points (service point and request point) and the connections between components.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataMigrationDiagram_TDMD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Migration Diagram - TOGAF Data Migration DiagramData migration is critical when implementing a package or packaged service-based solution.This is particularly true when an existing legacy application is replaced with a package or an enterprise is to be migrated to a larger packages packaged services footprint. Packages tend to have their own data model and during data migration the legacy application data may need to be transformed pr ior to loading into the package.Data migration activities will usually involve the following steps:Extract data from source applications (baseline systems)- Profile source data- Perform data transformation operations, including data quality processes:  - Standardize, normalize, de-duplicate source data (data cleansing)  - Match, merge, and consolidate data from different source(s)  - Source-to-target mappings- Load into target applications (target systems)The purpose of the Data Migration diagram is to show the flow of data from the source to the target applications. The diagram will provide a visual representation of the spread of sources targets and serve as a tool for data auditing and establishing traceability. This diagram can be elaborated or enhanced as detailed as necessary. For example, the diagram can contain just an overall layout of migration landscape or could go into individual application metadata element level of detail.

enumValues.name: TOGAFBusinessServiceInformationDiagram_TBSID
enumValues.description: TOGAF Business Service/Information Diagram - TOGAF Business Service/Information DiagramThe Business Service Information diagram shows the information needed to support one or more business services. The Business Service Information diagram shows what data is consumed by or produced by a business service and may also show the source of information.The Business Service Information diagram shows an initial representation of the information present within the architecture and therefore forms a basis for elaboration and refinement within Phase C (Data Architecture).

enumValues.name: CityPlanningDiagram_URB
enumValues.description: City planning diagram - City planning diagramEnterprise information systems develop with wide differences over time to suit projects. Different types of applications are randomly accumulated from mergers acquisitions or from consolidation deconsolidation. In large enterprises, there generally is significant redundancy in the data, services, and their use cases.Under these conditions, it becomes increasingly difficult to integrate new applications into existing information systems and to handle technological evolutions.The purpose of  city planning  for information systems is to define the main principles in the implementation and construction of computer applications, to ensure consistency throughout while decreasing the costs of building and integrating new applications. This should improve the company s ability to respond to a constantly changing environment.

enumValues.name: TOGAFProcessFlowDiagram_TPFD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Process Flow Diagram - TOGAF Process Flow DiagramThe purpose of the Process Flow diagram is to depict all models and mappings related to the process metamodel entity.Process Flow diagrams show sequential flow of control between activities and may utilize swimlane techniques to represent ownership and realization of process steps. For example, the application that supports a process step may be shown as a swim-lane.In addition to showing a sequence of activity, process flows can also be used to detail the controls that apply to a process, the events that trigger or result from completion of a process, and also the products that are generated from process execution.Process Flow diagrams are useful in elaborating the architecture with subject specialists, as they allow the specialist to describe  how the job is done  for a particular function. Through this process, each process step can become a more fine-grained function and can then in turn be elaborated as a process.

enumValues.description: TOGAF Environments and Locations Diagram - TOGAF Environments and Locations DiagramThe Environments and Locations diagram depicts which locations host which applications, identifies what technologies and or applications are used at which locations, and finally identifies the locations from which business users typically interact with the applications.This diagram should also show the existence and location of different deployment environments, including non-production environments, such as development and pre production.

enumValues.description: Enterprise Phase Tree Diagram - Enterprise Phase Tree DiagramAn Enterprise Phase Tree Diagram is a diagram showing the hierarchy of Enterprise Phase.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataLifecycleDiagram_TDLD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Lifecycle Diagram - TOGAF Data Lifecycle DiagramThe Data Lifecycle diagram is an essential part of managing business data throughout its lifecycle from conception until disposal within the constraints of the business process.The data is considered as an entity in its own right, decoupled from business process and activity. Each change in state is represented on the diagram which may include the event or rules that trigger that change in state.The separation of data from process allows common data requirements to be identified which enables resource sharing to be achieved more effectively.

enumValues.name: SystemProcessDiagram_BPMNSYSPROC
enumValues.description: System Process Diagram - System Process DiagramThis diagram is used to describe a system process using the BPMN notation. You can show the sequences of tasks, the conditioning and the events. Tasks can be assigned to participants that represent applications, IT services or org-units (for interactive tasks).This representation of a process is used to answer the question: how does my system work?

You can show the sequences of Value Stages, the conditioning and the events. Value Stages can be assigned to participants that represent the skills needed to perform them.This representation of a Value Stream is used to respond to the question: which skill do I need?

enumValues.name: ClassDiagram_MOBJ
enumValues.description: Class Diagram - Class DiagramA class diagram is used to represent the static structure of a system, particularly the types of objects manipulated in the system, their internal structure, and the relationships between them.

enumValues.name: TOGAFGoalObjectiveServiceDiagram_TGOSD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Goal/Objective/Service Diagram - TOGAF Goal/Objective/Service DiagramThe purpose of a Goal Objective Service diagram is to define the ways in which a service contributes to the achievement of a business vision or strategy.Services are associated with the drivers, goals, objectives, and measures that they support, allowing the enterprise to understand which services contribute to similar aspects of business performance. The Goal Objective Service diagram also provides qualitative input on what constitutes high performance for a particular service.

enumValues.name: StateDiagram_MTRE
enumValues.description: State Diagram - State DiagramA state diagram describes the evolution over time of an object of a certain class, and shows its behavior in response to interactions with other objects (internal or external to the studied system) in its environment.

enumValues.name: ApplicationStructureDiagram_ASD
enumValues.description: Application Structure Diagram - Application Structure DiagramAn Application Structure Diagram displays graphically the first level components of an Application, the access points (service request points) and the connections between the components.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataSecurityDiagram_TDSD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Security Diagram - TOGAF Data Security DiagramData is considered as an asset to the enterprise and data security simply means ensuring that enterprise data is not compromised and that access to it is suitably controlled.The purpose of the Data Security diagram is to depict which actor (person, organization, or system) can access which enterprise data. This relationship can be shown in a matrix form between two objects or can be shown as a mapping.The diagram can also be used to demonstrate compliance with data privacy laws and other applicable regulations (HIPAA, SOX, etc). This diagram should also consider any trust implications where an enterprise s partners or other parties may have access to the company s systems, such as an outsourced situation where information may be managed by other people and may even be hosted in a different country.

enumValues.name: OrganizationalChart_ORGANIGRAMME
enumValues.description: Organizational Chart - Organizational ChartThis diagram provides the description of the org-unit structure.Both hierarchical and functional dependencies can be shown.

enumValues.description: Application Architecture Diagram - Application Architecture DiagramAn Application Architecture Diagram describes the software environment of an application, a site, an org-unit, or for the entire company

enumValues.description: Relational Diagram - Relational DiagramA relational diagram describes a database: It represents the physical data structures used by programs.

enumValues.name: UseCaseDiagram_MUTI
enumValues.description: Use Case Diagram - Use Case DiagramUse case diagrams show actors and use cases together with their relationships. The use cases represent functionality of a system as manifested to external interactors with the system or the classifier.

enumValues.description: Application Tree - Application Tree DiagramThis diagram describes an application through a tree diagram of its components (sub-applications and services).

enumValues.name: TechnicalArchitectureDiagram_MAT
enumValues.description: Technical Architecture Diagram - Technical Architecture DiagramThe Technical Architecture Diagram (TAD) focuses on the hardware architecture needed to run the software. This type of diagram provides a detailed description of the technical architecture: network management, information flows, routing, and so on.The TAD also allows you to choose the correct hardware configuration for your applications and databases, plus the networks used to exchange information.

enumValues.name: BusinessServiceTreeDiagram_BSTD
enumValues.description: Business Service Tree Diagram - Business Service Tree DiagramA Business Service Tree Diagram represents the hierarchical structure of Business Services.

enumValues.name: BusinessFunctionalAreaDiagram_BF_ARC
enumValues.description: Business Functional Area Diagram - BA - Business Functional Area Diagram

enumValues.name: TOGAFPlatformDecompositionDiagram_TPDD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Platform Decomposition Diagram - TOGAF Platform Decomposition DiagramThe Platform Decomposition diagram depicts the technology platform that supports the operations of the Information Systems Architecture. The diagram covers all aspects of the infrastructure platform and provides an overview of the enterprise s technology platform. The diagram can be expanded to map the technology platform to appropriate application components within a specific functional or process area. This diagram may show details of specification, such as product versions, number of CPUs, etc. or simply could be an informal  eye-chart  providing an overview of the technical environment.

enumValues.name: CommunicationDiagram_COMMUNICATION
enumValues.description: Communication Diagram - Communication Diagram (UML2)Communication Diagrams focus on the interaction between lifelines where the architecture of the internal structure and how this corresponds with the message passing is central. The sequencing of messages is given through a sequence numbering scheme.The communication diagram is a simplified representation of the sequence diagram, concentrating on message exchanges between objects within an interaction.

enumValues.name: ActivityDiagramUMLTwo_ACTIVIYYDIAGUMLTwo
enumValues.description: Activity Diagram (UML2) - Activity Diagram (UML2)An activity diagram describes the sequence and conditions coordinating actions as well as the object flows exchanged during processing.These actions can be initiated because other actions finish executing, because objects and data become available, or because events occur external to the flow.

enumValues.name: InteractionOverviewDiagram_InteractionOverview
enumValues.description: Interaction Overview Diagram - Interaction Overview Diagram (UML2)Interaction Overview Diagrams define interactions through a variant of activity diagrams in a way that promotes overview of the control flow. They focus on the overview of the flow of control where the nodes are interactions or  interaction uses. The interaction overview diagram describes sequences possible between scenarios previously identified in the form of sequence diagrams.

enumValues.name: LogicalApplicationSystemEnvironmentDiagram_LASE
enumValues.description: Logical Application System Environment Diagram - SOIA - Logical Application System EnvironmentA Logical Application System Environment Diagram describes the interactions between a logical application system and its external partners in a specific context.

enumValues.name: Org_UnitOrganizationalChart_ORGUNITORGCHART
enumValues.description: Org-Unit Organizational Chart - Org-Unit Organizational ChartThis diagram provides the description of the org-unit structure.Both hierarchical and functional dependencies can be shown.

enumValues.name: TOGAFApplicationCommunicationDiagram_TACD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Application Communication Diagram - TOGAF Application Communication DiagramThe purpose of the Application Communication diagram is to depict all models and mappings related to communication between applications in the metamodel entity.It shows application components and interfaces between components. Interfaces may be associated with data entities where appropriate. Applications may be associated with business services where appropriate. Communication should be logical and should only show intermediary technology where it is architecturally relevant.

enumValues.name: TOGAFEventDiagram_TED
enumValues.description: TOGAF Event Diagram - TOGAF Event DiagramThe purpose of the Event diagram is to depict the relationship between events and process.Certain events - such as arrival of certain information (e.g., customer submits sales order) or a certain point in time (e.g., end of fiscal quarter) - cause work and certain actions need to be under taken within the business. These are often referred to as  business events  or simply  events  and are considered as triggers for a process. It is important to note that the event has to trigger a process and generate a business response or result.

enumValues.name: SystemProcessTreeDiagram_SYSPROC_TREE
enumValues.description: System Process Tree Diagram - System Process Tree DiagramA System Process Tree Diagram represents the hierarchical structure of  System Processs.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataDisseminationDiagram_TDDD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Dissemination Diagram - TOGAF Data Dissemination DiagramThe purpose of the Data Dissemination diagram is to show the relationship between data entity, business service, and application components. The diagram shows how the logical entities are to be physically realized by application components. This allows effective sizing to be carried out and the IT footprint to be refined. Moreover, by assigning business value to data, an indication of the business criticality of application components can be gained.Additionally, the diagram may show data replication and system ownership of the master reference for data. In this instance, it can show two copies and the master-copy relationship between them. This diagram can include services; that is, services encapsulate data and they reside in an application, or services that reside on an application and access data encapsulated within the application.

enumValues.name: TOGAFFunctionalDecompositionDiagram_TFDD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Functional Decomposition Diagram - TOGAF Functional Decomposition DiagramThe purpose of the Functional Decomposition diagram is to show on a single page the capabilities of an organization that are relevant to the consideration of an architecture. By examining the capabilities of an organization from a functional perspective, it is possible to quickly develop models of what the organization does without being dragged into extended debate on how the organization does it.Once a basic Functional Decomposition diagram has been developed, it becomes possible to layer heat-maps on top of this diagram to show scope and decisions. For example, thecapabilities to be implemented in different phases of a change program.

enumValues.name: RiskDiagram_RISKD

enumValues.name: PackageDiagram_MPAC
enumValues.description: Package Diagram - Package DiagramA package diagram divides the classes into different packages, in order to partition the work involved in specification and development. Interfaces may be associated with data entities where appropriate. Applications may be associated with business services where appropriate. Communication should be logical and should only show intermediary technology where it is architecturally relevant.

enumValues.name: ApplicationSystemEnvironmentScenario_APPSYSENVINTSCENARIO

properties.name: RecoveryPointObjectiveRPO
properties.description: The Recovery Point Objective (RPO) determines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time.Four levels of RPO need to be specified:- Critical (maximum tolerable data loss is seconds)- Serious (maximum tolerable data loss is minutes)- Significant (maximum tolerable data loss is hours)- Minor (maximum tolerable data loss is days)

properties.name: RecoveryTimeObjectiveRTO
properties.description: The Recovery Time Objective (RTO) determines the maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online. This covers, for example, restore data from back-up or fix of a failure.Four levels of RTO need to be specified:- Critical (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is seconds)- Serious (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is minutes)- Significant (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is hours)- Minor (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is days)

properties.name: WorkRecoveryTimeWRT
properties.description: The Work Recovery Time (WRT) determines the maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity. This could be, for example, checking the databases and logs, making sure the applications or services are running and are available.Four levels of WRT need to be specified:- Critical (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is seconds)- Serious (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is minutes)- Significant (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is hours)- Minor (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is days)

properties.name: MaximumTolerableDowntimeMTD
properties.description: Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) determines the maximum time a business can tolerate the absence or unavailability of a particular application.Downtime consists of two elements, the Recovery Time Objective and the Work Recovery Time: MTD = RTO + WRTMTD level will be calculated automatically according to RTO and WRT levels, it cannot be modified manually.-	Critical (maximum tolerable downtime is seconds)-	Serious (maximum tolerable downtime is minutes)-	Significant (maximum tolerable downtime is hours)-	Minor (maximum tolerable downtime is days)

properties.name: SLALevel

properties.name: DefferredPostgreSQL
properties.description: Upon creation, a constraint is given one of three characteristics: DEFERRABLE INITIALLY DEFERRED, DEFERRABLE INITIALLY IMMEDIATE, or NOT DEFERRABLE.The third class is always IMMEDIATE and is not affected by the SET CONSTRAINTS command.The first two classes start every transaction in the indicated mode, but their behavior can be changed within a transaction by SET CONSTRAINTS.When SET CONSTRAINTS changes the mode of a constraint from DEFERRED to IMMEDIATE, the new mode takes effect retroactively: any outstanding data modifications that would have been checkedat the end of the transaction are instead checked during the execution of the SET CONSTRAINTS command.

properties.name: MATCHTYPEPostgreSQL
properties.description: A value inserted into the referencing column(s) is matched against the values of the referencedtable and referenced columns using the given match type. There are three match types: MATCHFULL, MATCH PARTIAL, and MATCH SIMPLE (which is the default). MATCH FULL will not allowone column of a multicolumn foreign key to be null unless all foreign key columns are null; ifthey are all null, the row is not required to have a match in the referenced table. MATCH SIMPLEallows any of the foreign key columns to be null; if any of them are null, the row is not requiredto have a match in the referenced table. MATCH PARTIAL is not yet implemented. (Of course,NOT NULL constraints can be applied to the referencing column(s) to prevent these cases fromarising.)

properties.name: FillFactorPostgreSQL
properties.description: The fillfactor for a table is a percentage between 10 and 100. 100 (complete packing) is thedefault. When a smaller fillfactor is specified, INSERT operations pack table pages only to theindicated percentage; the remaining space on each page is reserved for updating rows on thatpage. This gives UPDATE a chance to place the updated copy of a row on the same page as theoriginal, which is more efficient than placing it on a different page. For a table whose entriesare never updated, complete packing is the best choice, but in heavily updated tables smallerfillfactors are appropriate. This parameter cannot be set for TOAST tables.

properties.name: VACUUMPostgreSQL
properties.description: Enables or disables the autovacuum daemon on a particular table. If true, the autovacuum daemonwill initiate a VACUUM operation on a particular table when the number of updated or deleted tuples exceeds autovacuum_vacuum_threshold plus autovacuum_vacuum_scale_factortimes the number of live tuples currently estimated to be in the relation.

properties.name: THRESHOLDPostgreSQL
properties.description: Minimum number of updated or deleted tuples before initiate a VACUUM operation on a particulartable.

properties.name: SCALEFACTORPostgreSQL
properties.description: Specifies a fraction of the table size to add to autovacuum_vacuum_threshold when decidingwhether to trigger a VACUUM. The default is 0.2 (20% of table size). This parameter can only beset in the postgresql.conf file or on the server command line. This setting can be overriddenfor individual tables by changing storage parameters.

properties.name: ANALYSETHRESHOLDPostgreSQL
properties.description: Specifies the minimum number of inserted, updated or deleted tuples needed to trigger anANALYZE in any one table. The default is 50 tuples. This parameter can only be set in thepostgresql.conf file or on the server command line. This setting can be overridden forindividual tables by changing storage parameters.

properties.name: ANALYSESCALEFACTORPostgreSQL
properties.description: Specifies a fraction of the table size to add to autovacuum_analyze_threshold when decidingwhether to trigger an ANALYZE. The default is 0.1 (10% of table size). This parameter canonly be set in the postgresql.conf file or on the server command line. This setting can beoverridden for individual tables by changing storage parameters.

properties.name: CostDelayPostgreSQL
properties.description: The length of time, in milliseconds, that the process will sleep when the cost limit has beenexceeded. The default value is zero, which disables the cost-based vacuum delay feature. Positivevalues enable cost-based vacuuming. Note that on many systems, the effective resolution of sleepdelays is 10 milliseconds; setting vacuum_cost_delay to a value that is not a multiple of 10might have the same results as setting it to the next higher multiple of 10.

properties.name: CostLimitPostgreSQL
properties.description: The accumulated cost that will cause the vacuuming process to sleep. The default value is 200.

properties.name: FREEZEMINAGEPostgreSQL
properties.description: Specifies the cutoff age (in transactions) that VACUUM should use to decide whether to replacetransaction IDs with FrozenXID while scanning a table. The default is 50 million transactions.Although users can set this value anywhere from zero to one billion, VACUUM will silently limitthe effective value to half the value of autovacuum_freeze_max_age, so that there is not anunreasonably short time between forced autovacuums.

properties.name: FREEZEMAXAGEPostgreSQL
properties.description: Specifies the maximum age (in transactions) that a tables pg_class.relfrozenxid field canattain before a VACUUM operation is forced to prevent transaction ID wraparound within thetable. Note that the system will launch autovacuum processes to prevent wraparound even whenautovacuum is otherwise disabled.

properties.name: FREEZETABLEAGEPostgreSQL
properties.description: VACUUM performs a whole-table scan if the tables pg_class.relminmxid field has reached theage specified by this setting. The default is 150 million multixacts. Although users can set thisvalue anywhere from zero to two billions, VACUUM will silently limit the effective value to 95%of autovacuum_multixact_freeze_max_age, so that a periodical manual VACUUM has a chanceto run before an anti-wraparound is launched for the table.

properties.name: TYPEMySQL
properties.description: Indicates table type1.1.1	Table types supported by MySQL             1.1.1.1	MyISAMMyISAM is the default storage engine as of MySQL 3.23. It is based on the ISAM code but has many useful extensions.Each MyISAM table is stored on disk in three files. The files have names that begin with the table name and have an extension to indicate the file type. An .frm file stores the table format. The data file has an .MYD (MYData) extension. The index file has an .MYI (MYIndex) extension.To specify explicitly that you want a MyISAM table, indicate that with an ENGINE table option:CREATE TABLE t (i INT) ENGINE = MYISAM;             1.1.1.3	MergeThe MERGE storage engine, also known as the MRG_MyISAM engine, is a collection of identical MyISAM tables that can be used as one.  Identical  means that all tables have identical column and index information.You cannot merge MyISAM tables in which the columns are listed in a different order, do not have exactly the same columns, or have the indexes in different order. However, any or all of the My-ISAM tables can be compressed with myisampack. See Section 8.5,  myisampack - Generate Compressed, Read-Only MyISAM Tables . Differences in table options such as AVG_ROW_LENGTH,MAX_ROWS, or PACK_KEYS do not matter.             1.1.1.4	InnoDBInnoDB provides MySQL with a transaction-safe (ACID compliant) storage engine that has commit,rollback, and crash recovery capabilities. InnoDB does locking on the row level and also provides an Oracle-style consistent non-locking read in SELECT statements. These features increase multi-user concurrencyand performance. There is no need for lock escalation in InnoDB because row-level locks fit in very little space. InnoDB also supports FOREIGN KEY constraints. You can freely mix InnoDB tables with tables from other MySQL storage engines, even within the same statement.

properties.name: ALGORITHMMySQL
properties.description: The optional ALGORITHM clause is a MySQL extension to standard SQL. ALGORITHM takes two values: MERGE or TEMPTABLE. By default there is no ALGORITHM clause. The algorithm affects how MySQL processes the view. For MERGE, the text of a statement that refers to the view and the view definition are merged such that parts of the view definition replace corresponding parts of the statement. For TEMPTABLE, the results from the view are retrieved into a temporary table, which then is used to execute the statement. A reason to choose TEMPTABLE explicitly is that locks can be released on underlying tables after the temporary table has been created and before it is used to finish processing the statement. This might result in quicker lock release than the MERGE algorithm so that other clients that use the view are not blocked as long. As mentioned earlier, MERGE is handled by merging corresponding parts of a view definition into the statement that refers to the view. The following examples briefly illustrate how the MERGE algorithm works. The examples assume that there is a view v_merge that has this definition: CREATE ALGORITHM = MERGE VIEW v_merge (vc1, vc2) ASSELECT c1, c2 FROM t WHERE c3 > 100;

properties.name: MAXROWSMySQL

properties.name: PACKKEYSMySQL
properties.description: PACK_KEYS takes effect only with MyISAM tables. Set this option to 1 if you want to have smallerindexes. This usually makes updates slower and reads faster. Setting the option to 0 disables allpacking of keys. Setting it to DEFAULT tells the storage engine to pack only long CHAR orVARCHAR columns.If you do not use PACK_KEYS, the default is to pack strings, but not numbers. If you usePACK_KEYS=1, numbers are packed as well.When packing binary number keys, MySQL uses prefix compression:- Every key needs one extra byte to indicate how many bytes of the previous key are the same forthe next key.- The pointer to the row is stored in high-byte-first order directly after the key, to improve compression.This means that if you have many equal keys on two consecutive rows, all following  same  keysusually only take two bytes (including the pointer to the row). Compare this to the ordinary casewhere the following keys takes storage_size_for_key + pointer_size (where thepointer size is usually 4). Conversely, you get a significant benefit from prefix compression only ifyou have many numbers that are the same. If all keys are totally different, you use one byte more perkey, if the key is not a key that can have NULL values. (In this case, the packed key length is storedin the same byte that is used to mark if a key is NULL.)

enumValues.name: TOGAFUseCaseDiagram_TUCD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Use Case Diagram - TOGAF Use Case DiagramA Business Use-Case diagram displays the relationships between consumers and providers of business services. Business services are consumed by actors or other business services and the Business Use-Case diagram provides added richness in describing business capability by illustrating how and when that capability is used.The purpose of the Business Use-Case diagram is to help to describe and validate the interaction between actors and their roles to processes and functions. As the architecture progresses, the use-case can evolve from the business level to include data, application, and technology details. Architectural business use-cases can also be re-used in systems design work.

enumValues.name: TOGAFApplicationAndUserLocationDiagram_TAULD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Application and User Location Diagram - TOGAF Application and User Location DiagramThe Application and User Location diagram shows the geographical distribution of applications.It can be used to show where applications are used by the end user; the distribution of where the host application is executed and or delivered in thin client scenarios; the distribution of where applications are developed, tested, and released; etc.Analysis can reveal opportunities for rationalization, as well as duplication and or gaps.The purpose of this diagram is to clearly depict the business locations from which business users typically interact with the applications, but also the hosting location of the application infrastr ucture.The diagram enables:- Identification of the number of package instances needed to sufficiently support the user population that may be spread out geographically- Estimation of the number and the type of user licenses for the package or other software- Estimation of the level of support needed for the users and location of support center- Selection of system management tools, structure, and management system required to support the enterprise users customers partners both locally and remotely- Appropriate planning for the technological components of the business, namely server sizing and network bandwidth, etc.- Performance considerations while implementing application and technology architecture solutionsUsers typically interact with applications in a variety of ways; for example:- To support the operations of the business day-to-day- To participate in the execution of a business process- To access information (look-up, read)- To develop the application- To administer and maintain the application

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataMigrationDiagram_TDMD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Migration Diagram - TOGAF Data Migration DiagramData migration is critical when implementing a package or packaged service-based solution.This is particularly true when an existing legacy application is replaced with a package or an enterprise is to be migrated to a larger packages packaged services footprint. Packages tend to have their own data model and during data migration the legacy application data may need to be transformed pr ior to loading into the package.Data migration activities will usually involve the following steps:Extract data from source applications (baseline systems)- Profile source data- Perform data transformation operations, including data quality processes:  - Standardize, normalize, de-duplicate source data (data cleansing)  - Match, merge, and consolidate data from different source(s)  - Source-to-target mappings- Load into target applications (target systems)The purpose of the Data Migration diagram is to show the flow of data from the source to the target applications. The diagram will provide a visual representation of the spread of sources targets and serve as a tool for data auditing and establishing traceability. This diagram can be elaborated or enhanced as detailed as necessary. For example, the diagram can contain just an overall layout of migration landscape or could go into individual application metadata element level of detail.

enumValues.name: CityPlanningDiagram_URB
enumValues.description: City planning diagram - City planning diagramEnterprise information systems develop with wide differences over time to suit projects. Different types of applications are randomly accumulated from mergers acquisitions or from consolidation deconsolidation. In large enterprises, there generally is significant redundancy in the data, services, and their use cases.Under these conditions, it becomes increasingly difficult to integrate new applications into existing information systems and to handle technological evolutions.The purpose of  city planning  for information systems is to define the main principles in the implementation and construction of computer applications, to ensure consistency throughout while decreasing the costs of building and integrating new applications. enumValues.name: TOGAFProcessFlowDiagram_TPFD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Process Flow Diagram - TOGAF Process Flow DiagramThe purpose of the Process Flow diagram is to depict all models and mappings related to the process metamodel entity.Process Flow diagrams show sequential flow of control between activities and may utilize swimlane techniques to represent ownership and realization of process steps. For example, the application that supports a process step may be shown as a swim-lane.In addition to showing a sequence of activity, process flows can also be used to detail the controls that apply to a process, the events that trigger or result from completion of a process, and also the products that are generated from process execution.Process Flow diagrams are useful in elaborating the architecture with subject specialists, as they allow the specialist to describe  how the job is done  for a particular function. Through this process, each process step can become a more fine-grained function and can then in turn be elaborated as a process.

enumValues.name: ServiceArchitectureDiagram_SAD
enumValues.description: Service Architecture Diagram - Service Architecture DiagramThis diagram details the exchanges between the components involved in the behavior of the service.

enumValues.name: OverviewOfBusinessFunctions_BFMD
enumValues.description: Overview of Business Functions - Overview of Business FunctionsThis diagram presents an assessment of flows between the enterprise s main business functions.This assessment is made through the use of channels which list the flows exchanged between activities (involvement of business functions within business processes).

enumValues.name: OrganizationalProcessTreeDiagram_OPTD
enumValues.description: Organizational Process Tree Diagram - Organizational Process Tree DiagramAn Organizational Process Tree Diagram is a diagram showing the hierarchy of Organizational Process.

enumValues.name: TOGAFEnvironmentsAndLocationsDiagram_TELD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Environments and Locations Diagram - TOGAF Environments and Locations DiagramThe Environments and Locations diagram depicts which locations host which applications, identifies what technologies and or applications are used at which locations, and finally identifies the locations from which business users typically interact with the applications.This diagram should also show the existence and location of different deployment environments, including non-production environments, such as development and pre production.

enumValues.name: ResourceArchitectureTreeDiagram_CCTD
enumValues.description: Resource Architecture Tree Diagram - Resource Architecture Tree DiagramA resource architecture tree is a diagram showing the hierarchy of resource architectures.

enumValues.name: ConceptLifeCycleStructureDiagram_DICSTATEMACHINESD
enumValues.description: Concept Life Cycle Structure Diagram - Concept Life Cycle Structure Diagram

enumValues.name: BatchPlanningStructureDiagram_BPLAN_STRUCT
enumValues.description: Batch Planning Structure Diagram - Batch Planning Structure Diagram

enumValues.name: ApplicationSystemTechnicalArchitectureDiagram_ITARC_ASTA_TAD
enumValues.description: Application System Technical Architecture Diagram - IT Architecture - ASTA - Technical Architecture DiagramThis Technical Architecture diagram represents the Technical Architectures and the Technical Data Areas of the described Application System Technical Architecture as well as the techniques used for their communications.

enumValues.name: EnterprisePhaseTreeDiagram_EPTD
enumValues.description: Enterprise Phase Tree Diagram - Enterprise Phase Tree DiagramAn Enterprise Phase Tree Diagram is a diagram showing the hierarchy of Enterprise Phase.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataLifecycleDiagram_TDLD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Lifecycle Diagram - TOGAF Data Lifecycle DiagramThe Data Lifecycle diagram is an essential part of managing business data throughout its lifecycle from conception until disposal within the constraints of the business process.The data is considered as an entity in its own right, decoupled from business process and activity. Each change in state is represented on the diagram which may include the event or rules that trigger that change in state.The separation of data from process allows common data requirements to be identified which enables resource sharing to be achieved more effectively.

enumValues.name: SystemProcessDiagram_BPMNSYSPROC
enumValues.description: System Process Diagram - System Process DiagramThis diagram is used to describe a system process using the BPMN notation. You can show the sequences of tasks, the conditioning and the events. Tasks can be assigned to participants that represent applications, IT services or org-units (for interactive tasks).This representation of a process is used to answer the question: how does my system work?

enumValues.name: GlobalApplicationFlowMap_GLOBINTSCEDIAG
enumValues.description: Global Application Flow Map - Global Application Flow Map

enumValues.name: ValueStreamDiagram_BPMNFUNPROC
enumValues.description: Value Stream Diagram - Functional Process DiagramThis diagram is used to describe a Value Stream, using the BPMN notation. You can show the sequences of Value Stages, the conditioning and the events. Value Stages can be assigned to participants that represent the skills needed to perform them.This representation of a Value Stream is used to respond to the question: which skill do I need?

enumValues.name: ScenarioOfApplicationFlowsDiagram_APPLIINTERSCENA
enumValues.description: Scenario of Application Flows Diagram - Scenario of Application Flows

enumValues.name: ClassDiagram_MOBJ
enumValues.description: Class Diagram - Class DiagramA class diagram is used to represent the static structure of a system, particularly the types of objects manipulated in the system, their internal structure, and the relationships between them.

enumValues.name: TOGAFGoalObjectiveServiceDiagram_TGOSD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Goal/Objective/Service Diagram - TOGAF Goal/Objective/Service DiagramThe purpose of a Goal Objective Service diagram is to define the ways in which a service contributes to the achievement of a business vision or strategy.Services are associated with the drivers, goals, objectives, and measures that they support, allowing the enterprise to understand which services contribute to similar aspects of business performance. The Goal Objective Service diagram also provides qualitative input on what constitutes high performance for a particular service.

enumValues.name: StateDiagram_MTRE
enumValues.description: State Diagram - State DiagramA state diagram describes the evolution over time of an object of a certain class, and shows its behavior in response to interactions with other objects (internal or external to the studied system) in its environment.

enumValues.name: ApplicationStructureDiagram_ASD
enumValues.description: Application Structure Diagram - Application Structure DiagramAn Application Structure Diagram displays graphically the first level components of an Application, the access points (service request points) and the connections between the components.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataSecurityDiagram_TDSD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Security Diagram - TOGAF Data Security DiagramData is considered as an asset to the enterprise and data security simply means ensuring that enterprise data is not compromised and that access to it is suitably controlled.The purpose of the Data Security diagram is to depict which actor (person, organization, or system) can access which enterprise data. This relationship can be shown in a matrix form between two objects or can be shown as a mapping.The diagram can also be used to demonstrate compliance with data privacy laws and other applicable regulations (HIPAA, SOX, etc). This diagram should also consider any trust implications where an enterprise s partners or other parties may have access to the company s systems, such as an outsourced situation where information may be managed by other people and may even be hosted in a different country.

enumValues.name: OrganizationalChart_ORGANIGRAMME
enumValues.description: Organizational Chart - Organizational ChartThis diagram provides the description of the org-unit structure.Both hierarchical and functional dependencies can be shown.

enumValues.name: ApplicationArchitectureDiagram_MODELE_APPLICATION
enumValues.description: Application Architecture Diagram - Application Architecture DiagramAn Application Architecture Diagram describes the software environment of an application, a site, an org-unit, or for the entire company

enumValues.name: RelationalDiagram_MR
enumValues.description: Relational Diagram - Relational DiagramA relational diagram describes a database: It represents the physical data structures used by programs.

enumValues.name: UseCaseDiagram_MUTI
enumValues.description: Use Case Diagram - Use Case DiagramUse case diagrams show actors and use cases together with their relationships. The use cases represent functionality of a system as manifested to external interactors with the system or the classifier.

enumValues.name: ApplicationTree_ARBRE_APPLICATIF
enumValues.description: Application Tree - Application Tree DiagramThis diagram describes an application through a tree diagram of its components (sub-applications and services).

enumValues.name: TechnicalArchitectureDiagram_MAT
enumValues.description: Technical Architecture Diagram - Technical Architecture DiagramThe Technical Architecture Diagram (TAD) focuses on the hardware architecture needed to run the software. This type of diagram provides a detailed description of the technical architecture: network management, information flows, routing, and so on.The TAD also allows you to choose the correct hardware configuration for your applications and databases, plus the networks used to exchange information.

enumValues.name: BusinessServiceTreeDiagram_BSTD
enumValues.description: Business Service Tree Diagram - Business Service Tree DiagramA Business Service Tree Diagram represents the hierarchical structure of Business Services.

enumValues.name: BusinessFunctionalAreaDiagram_BF_ARC
enumValues.description: Business Functional Area Diagram - BA - Business Functional Area Diagram

enumValues.name: TOGAFPlatformDecompositionDiagram_TPDD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Platform Decomposition Diagram - TOGAF Platform Decomposition DiagramThe Platform Decomposition diagram depicts the technology platform that supports the operations of the Information Systems Architecture. The diagram covers all aspects of the infrastructure platform and provides an overview of the enterprise s technology platform. The diagram can be expanded to map the technology platform to appropriate application components within a specific functional or process area. This diagram may show details of specification, such as product versions, number of CPUs, etc. or simply could be an informal  eye-chart  providing an overview of the technical environment.

enumValues.name: CommunicationDiagram_COMMUNICATION
enumValues.description: Communication Diagram - Communication Diagram (UML2)Communication Diagrams focus on the interaction between lifelines where the architecture of the internal structure and how this corresponds with the message passing is central. The sequencing of messages is given through a sequence numbering scheme.The communication diagram is a simplified representation of the sequence diagram, concentrating on message exchanges between objects within an interaction.

enumValues.name: ActivityDiagramUMLTwo_ACTIVIYYDIAGUMLTwo
enumValues.description: Activity Diagram (UML2) - Activity Diagram (UML2)An activity diagram describes the sequence and conditions coordinating actions as well as the object flows exchanged during processing.These actions can be initiated because other actions finish executing, because objects and data become available, or because events occur external to the flow.

enumValues.name: InteractionOverviewDiagram_InteractionOverview
enumValues.description: Interaction Overview Diagram - Interaction Overview Diagram (UML2)Interaction Overview Diagrams define interactions through a variant of activity diagrams in a way that promotes overview of the control flow. They focus on the overview of the flow of control where the nodes are interactions or  interaction uses. The interaction overview diagram describes sequences possible between scenarios previously identified in the form of sequence diagrams.

enumValues.name: LogicalApplicationSystemEnvironmentDiagram_LASE
enumValues.description: Logical Application System Environment Diagram - SOIA - Logical Application System EnvironmentA Logical Application System Environment Diagram describes the interactions between a logical application system and its external partners in a specific context.

enumValues.name: Org_UnitOrganizationalChart_ORGUNITORGCHART
enumValues.description: Org-Unit Organizational Chart - Org-Unit Organizational ChartThis diagram provides the description of the org-unit structure.Both hierarchical and functional dependencies can be shown.

enumValues.name: TOGAFApplicationCommunicationDiagram_TACD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Application Communication Diagram - TOGAF Application Communication DiagramThe purpose of the Application Communication diagram is to depict all models and mappings related to communication between applications in the metamodel entity.It shows application components and interfaces between components. Interfaces may be associated with data entities where appropriate. Applications may be associated with business services where appropriate. Communication should be logical and should only show intermediary technology where it is architecturally relevant.

enumValues.name: TOGAFEventDiagram_TED
enumValues.description: TOGAF Event Diagram - TOGAF Event DiagramThe purpose of the Event diagram is to depict the relationship between events and process.Certain events - such as arrival of certain information (e.g., customer submits sales order) or a certain point in time (e.g., end of fiscal quarter) - cause work and certain actions need to be under taken within the business. These are often referred to as  business events  or simply  events  and are considered as triggers for a process. It is important to note that the event has to trigger a process and generate a business response or result.

enumValues.name: SystemProcessTreeDiagram_SYSPROC_TREE
enumValues.description: System Process Tree Diagram - System Process Tree DiagramA System Process Tree Diagram represents the hierarchical structure of  System Processs.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataDisseminationDiagram_TDDD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Dissemination Diagram - TOGAF Data Dissemination DiagramThe purpose of the Data Dissemination diagram is to show the relationship between data entity, business service, and application components. The diagram shows how the logical entities are to be physically realized by application components. This allows effective sizing to be carried out and the IT footprint to be refined. Moreover, by assigning business value to data, an indication of the business criticality of application components can be gained.Additionally, the diagram may show data replication and system ownership of the master reference for data. In this instance, it can show two copies and the master-copy relationship between them. This diagram can include services; that is, services encapsulate data and they reside in an application, or services that reside on an application and access data encapsulated within the application.

enumValues.name: TOGAFFunctionalDecompositionDiagram_TFDD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Functional Decomposition Diagram - TOGAF Functional Decomposition DiagramThe purpose of the Functional Decomposition diagram is to show on a single page the capabilities of an organization that are relevant to the consideration of an architecture. By examining the capabilities of an organization from a functional perspective, it is possible to quickly develop models of what the organization does without being dragged into extended debate on how the organization does it.Once a basic Functional Decomposition diagram has been developed, it becomes possible to layer heat-maps on top of this diagram to show scope and decisions. For example, thecapabilities to be implemented in different phases of a change program.

enumValues.name: RiskDiagram_RISKD
enumValues.description: Risk Diagram - Risk DiagramThis diagram is used to describe where a risk can occur, its impacts and how it can be prevented.

enumValues.name: StateConceptStructureDiagram_SCPTINFODIAG
enumValues.description: State Concept Structure Diagram - State Concept StructureDiagramThis diagram is used to describe a concept state structure. It looks like a concept structure diagram.

enumValues.name: ServiceTaxonomyDiagram_SDVD
enumValues.description: Service Taxonomy Diagram - Service Taxonomy DiagramThis diagram describes the taxonomy of the service definition through a tree diagram of its specializations and generalizations.

enumValues.name: Cause_and_EffectDiagram_CED
enumValues.description: Cause-and-Effect Diagram - Causes/Effects DiagramThe cause-and-effect diagram (also called Ishikawa diagram or fishbone diagram) is a tool that enables identification of the possible causes of an observed effect and therefore determination of a means of solving the problems.

enumValues.name: GeneralOrganizationalChart_GENORGCHART
enumValues.description: General Organizational Chart - General Organizational ChartThis diagram provides a general description of the enterprise management structureIt enables description of both hierarchical and functional dependencies.

enumValues.name: TimelineDiagram_TIMELINE
enumValues.description: Timeline Diagram - Timeline DiagramThe Timeline diagram presents the sequance of key timespots of an organization or a project. A timespot can be represented by a fixed date or a limited time period.

enumValues.name: BusinessFunctionStructureDiagram_ONSD
enumValues.description: Business Function Structure Diagram - Operational Node Structure DiagramA Operational Node Structure Diagram displays graphically the first level components of a Business Function, the access points (service request points) and the connections between the components.

enumValues.name: OrganizationEnvironmentDiagram_ORGENVDIAG
enumValues.description: Organization Environment Diagram - Organization Environment Diagram

enumValues.name: TOGAFEnterpriseManageabilityDiagram_TEMD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Enterprise Manageability Diagram - TOGAF Enterprise Manageability DiagramThe Enterprise Manageability diagram shows how one or more applications interact with application and technology components that support operational management of a solution.This diagram is really a filter on the Application Communication diagram, specifically for enterprise management class software.Analysis can reveal duplication and gaps, and opportunities in the IT service management operation of an organization.

enumValues.name: PackageDiagram_MPAC
enumValues.description: Package Diagram - Package DiagramA package diagram divides the classes into different packages, in order to partition the work involved in specification and development. A class should only appear in a single package. Dividing into packages is generally carried out so as to minimise interactions between different packages.

enumValues.name: IDEFDataAreaDiagram_IDEFDAD
enumValues.description: IDEF Data Area Diagram - IDEF Data Area Diagram

enumValues.name: TOGAFCommunicationsEngineeringDiagram_TCED
enumValues.description: TOGAF Communications Engineering Diagram - TOGAF Communications Engineering DiagramThe purpose of the Application Communication diagram is to depict all models and mappings related to communication between applications in the metamodel entity.It shows application components and interfaces between components. Interfaces may be associated with data entities where appropriate. Applications may be associated with business services where appropriate. Communication should be logical and should only show intermediary technology where it is architecturally relevant.

enumValues.name: ApplicationSystemEnvironmentScenario_APPSYSENVINTSCENARIO
enumValues.description: Application System Environment Scenario - Application System Environment Scenario

enumValues.name: LogicalApplicationSystemStructureDiagram_SSASD
enumValues.description: Logical Application System Structure Diagram - Logical Application System Structure DiagramDiagram describing the internal structure of a Logical Application System, its provided or requested services, its conducted processes, its components and their interactions as well as end-users and their interactions with components.

enumValues.name: TechnicalFunctionalityDiagram_TECHFUNCTD
enumValues.description: Technical Functionality Diagram - Technical Functionality DiagramA Technical Functionality Diagram is a representation of the set of functionalities with their dependencies that, jointly, define the scope of an equipment item (hardware or software) corresponding to the Technical Functionality.

enumValues.name: TechnicalFunctionalityMapDiagram_TECHFUNCTMD
enumValues.description: Technical Functionality Map Diagram - Technical Functionality Map DiagramA Technical Functionality Map Diagram is a representation of the set of functionalities with their dependencies that, jointly, define the scope of an equipment item (hardware or software) corresponding to the Technical Functionality Map.

enumValues.name: UserInterfaceDiagram_UI
enumValues.description: User Interface Diagram - User Interface DiagramThe user interface diagram allows you to draw the graphical  interface of an interactive service or of a workflow operation.

enumValues.name: BusinessProcessDiagram_BPMNBIZPROC
enumValues.description: Business Process Diagram - Business Process Diagram (BPMN)This diagram is used to describe a structure of the business of the company. It presents product or service offerings, the composition of business processes that produce them and their implementation by functional, organizational or system processes. This diagram uses a subset of the BPMN notation.

enumValues.name: ProjectCompositionDiagram_PROJ_C
enumValues.description: Project Composition Diagram - Project Composition DiagramA Project Composition Diagram displays graphically the first level components of a EA Project.

enumValues.name: ApplicationEnvironmentScenarioSequenceDiagram_APPENVSCENSEQ
enumValues.description: Application Environment Scenario Sequence Diagram - Application Environment Scenario Sequence Diagram

enumValues.name: ArtifactAssemblyDiagram_ARTIFACT_ASSEMBLY
enumValues.description: Artifact Assembly Diagram - Artifact Assembly DiagramAn Artifact Assembly Diagram displays graphically the first level components of an Artifact, the access points (service request points, communication ports) and the connections between the components.

enumValues.name: InfrastructureAssemblyStructureDiagram_ITA_IASD
enumValues.description: Infrastructure Assembly Structure Diagram - IT Infrastructure Structure Diagram

enumValues.name: BusinessFunctionHierarchyDiagram_ONTD
enumValues.description: Business Function Hierarchy Diagram - Business Function Hierarchy DiagramThis diagram describes a business function through a tree diagram of its components.

enumValues.name: InteractionScenarioDiagram_APPINTERACTSCENARIO
enumValues.description: Interaction Scenario Diagram - Application Interaction Scenario DiagramThis diagram is used to describe a scenario enabling determination of interactions between sub-applications or services required to implement a use case of an application.

enumValues.name: ApplicationScenarioSequenceDiagram_APPLIINTERSCENASEQ
enumValues.description: Application Scenario Sequence Diagram - Application Scenario Sequence Diagram

enumValues.description: Skill Map Diagram - BA - Skill Map Diagram

metaclass.name: Application
metaclass.description: An application is a software component that can be deployed and provides users with a set of functionalities.

properties.name: Name
properties.description: Short Name of the object (posibility to get the long name with an argument)

properties.name: ApplicationCode
properties.description: The code is a unique mnemonic for your application. This mnemonic should follow the code standards used in your organization.

properties.name: CloudComputing
properties.description: Cloud Computing  defines how the application should be installed1 : On premises  the Appilcation is installed and runs on computers on the premises (in the building) the compagny2 : Infrastructure as a Service (IAAS): Application is installed and runs on an external provider infrastructure (physical or virtual machines and other additional resources such as images in a virtual-machine image-library, raw (block) and file-based storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles)3 : Platform as a Service (PAAS): Application is installed and runs on an external provider computing platform including operating system, programming language execution environment, database, and web server. Internal external developers can develop and run their software solutions on a cloud platform4 : Software as a Service (SAAS): Application is designed, installed and runs by an external delivery partner. Some customization can be implemented during the design phase

properties.name: VersionNumber
properties.description: Indicates the current version number of the application.

properties.name: RequiredMemorySize
properties.description: Indicates the memory required for execution of the application.

properties.name: Prefix
properties.description: Prefix  put at the beginning of the name of the objects generated from an application, a database, etc.

properties.name: ApplicationStereotype
properties.description: In a n-tiers architecture,  this attribute clarify the tier implemented by the application

enumValues.name: PresentationLogic
enumValues.description: Presentation logic - Application Stereotype-2Tier in charge of end-user interface navigation

enumValues.name: BusinessLogic
enumValues.description: Business logic - Application Stereotype-3Tier in charge of business treatments

enumValues.name: DataManagement
enumValues.description: Data management - Application Stereotype-4Tier in charge of data access

properties.name: ApplicationType
properties.description: Specifies if the application is a software package, a specific development, system software (Windows NT, etc.), middleware software or office automation software (Word, Excel, etc.).

properties.name: CurrentState
properties.description: This attribute give the current state of the object in its object live.

properties.name: GlobalExpense
properties.description: aggregation of costs of Applications + Deployment of Application for the current year

properties.name: CurrentNumberOfUsers
properties.description: Sum of the numbers of users specified on all deployment context that are in production today.

properties.name: CostPerUser
properties.description: Calculate the cost per user (aggregation of costs of Applications + Deployment of Application divided by all users specified on deployment context).

properties.name: RankAPM
properties.description: The Rank summarizes the evaluation criteria of the applicaction: the technical efficiency, the functional support and business value. If the sum of the evaluation criteria gives: 3 or 4 the Rank is 1 star5 or 6 the Rank is 2 stars 7 or 8 the Rank is 3 stars 9 or 10 the Rank is 4 stars 11 or 12 the Rank is 5 stars If the sum is less than 3 the application is ranked 0 stars.

properties.name: TechnologyCompliance
properties.description: Technological compliance is calculated as follows:If all technologies used by the application have as enterprise Standard the value  Recommended , technology Compliance takes the value  Recommended .If one of the technologies used by the application has as enterprise Standard the value  Prohibited , technology Compliance takes the value  Prohibited .If at least one of the technologies used by the application has as enterprise Standard the value  Accepted  ,technology Compliance takes the value  Accepted . If the application does not use any technology, or if all technologies used by the application have as enterprise Standard the value  Unknown , technology Compliance takes the value  Unknown .

properties.name: Expenses
properties.description: This present the total expense of the object for the current year from the 1st of january to the 31st of december

properties.name: CapitalExpenses
properties.description: This present the capital expense of the object for the current year from the 1st of january to the 31st of december

properties.name: OperatingExpenses
properties.description: This present the operating expense of the object for the current year from the 1st of january to the 31st of december

properties.name: CASTHighlightID
properties.description: CAST Highlight Application ID

properties.name: BusinessValueAPM
properties.description: This attribute reflect the value of the last assessment session for Business Value of the application.The value is obtained either from a direct evaluation or it is the result of an evaluation per questionnaire.

properties.name: FunctionalSupportAPM
properties.description: This attribute reflect the value of the last assessment session for the Technical Efficiency of the application.The value is obtained either from a direct evaluation or it is the result of an evaluation per questionnaire.

properties.name: TechnicalEfficiencyAPM
properties.description: This attribute reflect the value of the last assessment session for the Technical Efficiency of the application.The value is obtained either from a direct evaluation or it is the result of an evaluation per questionnaire.

properties.name: BeginLifeDate
properties.description: Beginning of the production period

properties.name: EndLifeDate
properties.description: End of the production period

properties.name: ClosingDateCast
properties.description: End date of the campaign that captured the application information in Cast Highlight.

properties.name: SoftwareResiliencyScoreCASTHighligh
properties.description: Express in %.Software Resiliency indicates programming best practices that make software bullet-proof, more robust and secure. This index is derived through technology-specific code analysis that searches for the presence of code patterns and bad programming practices that may comprise the reliability of the software at short term. Higher is the Software Resiliency, lower is the likelihood of defects occurring in production.Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: SoftwareResiliency
properties.description: Thresholds used for Software Resiliency:High (green): value >= 71.0 Medium (orange): value >= 57.0 Low (red): value < 57.0Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: SoftwareAgilityScore
properties.description: Express in %.Software Agility indicates the easiness of a development team to understand and maintain an application. This index is derived through technology-specific code analysis that searches for the presence of embedded documentation and code readability good practices.Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: SoftwareAgility
properties.description: Thresholds used for Software Agility categories:High (green): value >= 78.0Medium (orange): value >= 51.0Low (red): value < 51.0Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: SoftwareEleganceScoreCASTHighligh
properties.description: Express in %.Software Elegance measures the ability to deliver software value with less code complexity. A low Software Elegance score indicates decreased quality in the code resulting in higher defects that become costly to fix at mid-term.Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: SoftwareEleganceThresholds
properties.description: Thresholds used for Software Elegance categories:High (green): value >= 88.0Medium (orange): value >= 66.0Low (red): value < 66.0Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: CloudReadyScoreCASTHighlight
properties.description: Express in %. Formula use the survey point reference and applay loss and gain points from the source code scan.

properties.name: CloudReadyScanCASTHighlight
properties.description: Express in %.

properties.name: TechnicalDebtCast
properties.description: Technical Debt measures the effort required to fix coding and architectural violations that remain in the code when an application is released.Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: NumberOfLinesOfCodeCast
properties.description: Number of Lines of Code scanned by Cast Highlight for the application.Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: NumberOfFilesCast
properties.description: Number of Files scanned by Cast Highlight for the application.Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: AggregationTypeAPM
properties.description: The Cost Aggregation Type explains if the cost of an application is counted in the Global Costs of Applications, or if the cost of this application is divided in the applications systems using the component.

properties.name: BackFiredFunctionPointsCASTHighlight
properties.description: Back-Fired Function Points (BFP) estimate the number of function points of an application. This code-derived metric is based on the lines of code, weighted by an abacus for a given technology. The abacus is taken from QSM <http:  www.qsm.com resources function-point-languages-table> (Quantitative Software Management).Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: SoftwareResiliencyQuartile
properties.description: Software Resiliency Quartile benchmark position of the application or technology.Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: RecoveryPointObjectiveRPO
properties.description: The Recovery Point Objective (RPO) determines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time.Four levels of RPO need to be specified:- Critical (maximum tolerable data loss is seconds)- Serious (maximum tolerable data loss is minutes)- Significant (maximum tolerable data loss is hours)- Minor (maximum tolerable data loss is days)

properties.name: RecoveryTimeObjectiveRTO
properties.description: The Recovery Time Objective (RTO) determines the maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online. This covers, for example, restore data from back-up or fix of a failure.Four levels of RTO need to be specified:- Critical (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is seconds)- Serious (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is minutes)- Significant (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is hours)- Minor (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is days)

properties.name: WorkRecoveryTimeWRT
properties.description: The Work Recovery Time (WRT) determines the maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity. This could be, for example, checking the databases and logs, making sure the applications or services are running and are available.Four levels of WRT need to be specified:- Critical (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is seconds)- Serious (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is minutes)- Significant (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is hours)- Minor (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is days)

properties.name: MaximumTolerableDowntimeMTD
properties.description: Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) determines the maximum time a business can tolerate the absence or unavailability of a particular application.Downtime consists of two elements, the Recovery Time Objective and the Work Recovery Time: MTD = RTO + WRTMTD level will be calculated automatically according to RTO and WRT levels, it cannot be modified manually.-	Critical (maximum tolerable downtime is seconds)-	Serious (maximum tolerable downtime is minutes)-	Significant (maximum tolerable downtime is hours)-	Minor (maximum tolerable downtime is days)

properties.name: SLALevel
properties.description: Service-level Agreement (SLA) is a contract between a service provider and its internal or external customers that documents what services the provider will furnish, to calculate the SLA, HOPEX users (Portfolio Manager, Application Owner) will need to fill information on:- Recovery point objective (RPO)- Recovery time objective (RTO)- Work Recovery Time (WRT)- Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)Then a SLA value will be proposed by HOPEX, if the result is not in line with user expectation, he will be able to change the SLA value manually.
